  "prompt": "Relation between change in celcius to change in fahrenhiet?",
  "response": "The relationship between changes in temperature in Celsius and Fahrenheit is linear. You can convert a change in temperature in Celsius (\u0394\u00b0C) to a change in temperature in Fahrenheit (\u0394\u00b0F) using the following conversion formula:\n\n\\[ \\Delta F = \\Delta C \\times \\frac{9}{5} \\]\n\nThis conversion factor (9/5 or 1.8) comes from the ratio of the scales between Celsius and Fahrenheit.\n\nHere's how it works:\n\n- If the temperature changes by 1 degree Celsius, that corresponds to a change of 1.8 degrees Fahrenheit.\n- If the temperature changes by 5 degrees Celsius, that corresponds to a change of \\( 5 \\times 1.8 = 9 \\) degrees Fahrenheit.\n\nThus, for any temperature change in Celsius, multiplying it by 1.8 gives you the equivalent temperature change in Fahrenheit.",
